<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>ABTA response to Transport Select Committee Inquiry</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ABTA – The Travel Association</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (WRT 011)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This response is submitted on behalf of the membership of ABTA – The Travel Association. ABTA was founded in 1950 and is the largest travel trade association in the UK, with around 1,200 members and over 5,000 retail outlets and offices. Our Members range </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from small, specialist tour operators and independent travel agencies specialising in business and leisure travel, through to publicly listed companies and household names. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The success of ABTA Members’ businesses is directly reliant on the UK’s aviation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">infrastructure; many of ABTA’s larger Members are themselves part of groups that own airlines. ABTA Members provide 90% of the package holidays sold in the UK, with Members also selling millions of independent travel arrangements. The provision of quality,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> efficient and competitively priced passenger air travel is vital to the business interests of Members.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uring that travellers can access and travel from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">airports, train stations and ports is an important part of our policy work. We have been calling fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r enhanced winter resilience on our roads, rail and airports for a number of years and we welcome efforts made by industry and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment to improve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">connectivity in winter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We also welcome the Committee’s continued interest in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensuring the provision of tim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ely, efficient, and reliable transport in all weather.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> There remain, however, a number of continuing challenges to overcome in relation to addressing winter resilience.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How resilient are the UK’s transport networks (including road, rail and air) to adverse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> winter weather?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In our October 2012 response to the Transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Select </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee, we highlighted the importance of aviation to the UK economy.  The aviation sector offers a wide range of benefits:  it facilitates business and leisure travel of British </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">citizens across the world; it brings business and visitors into the UK; it enables the import and export of goods; all of which contribute to a successful and growing UK economy. Aviation is an important part of the UK’s strat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">egic transport infrastructure.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> extreme weather, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aviation connectivity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can be put under considerable strain.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">London airports do experience problems with resilience and will continue to suffer unless and until capacity issues are addressed. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK’s two largest airports are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capacity constrained: Heathrow is currently operating at over 98%. Gatwick is the busiest single runway commercial airport in the world and is operating at around 78% with unused capacity only in the off-peak periods. This leaves little </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capacity spare for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recovery. Resilience therefore has a reputational impact on London’s key airports, particularly Heathrow, and this could impact on the choice of customers from around the globe to use the UK’s hub airport to connect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> onward flights.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome improve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ments in recent years in resilience at the London airports but we remain concerned that without further increased resilience measures – including additional capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> what should be a minor disruption as a result of adverse weather or other incidents can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">result in a severe delay. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Spare capacity is not only essential for jobs and growth but also for efficient management of incidents and delays, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regardless of what causes them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Contrast this with the continental airports at Paris Charles de Gaulle, Amsterdam</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Schiphol, Frankfurt and Madrid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> all of which have substantially more runways with the capacity to recover quickly.  This gives our continental competition a speedier recovery time in the ev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent of European wide disruption; this means </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fewer flights are dela</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">yed or cancelled and fewer passengers delayed. In essence, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> greater capacity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at the aforementioned airports</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reduces the impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of adverse weather or other operational challenges,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lessening the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resulting economic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no room for trade</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-offs at capacity constrained airports, other than reducing the number of flights, which is completely unacceptable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for airlines and for passengers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  This is yet another reason to increase runway capacity.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:22.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK’s historic connectivity advantage cannot </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be taken for granted. To maintain London’s leading status in aviation connectivity, the Government must recognise that the necessary growth in capacity, improvements in surface connectivity, and the quality of the passenger experience are vital conditions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for a successful economy.  The Government should plan now to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure that the UK remains a significant player in the international aviation industry. Additional capacity would not only provide for future UK economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will also allow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> time for recov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ery in the event of disruption. In recent years we have seen the need for additional capacity to allow for restoration of flight programmes due to extreme weat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">her, aircraft crash landings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and unforeseen circumstances. Spare capacity is vital to allow time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the airport and airlines to implement recovery plans. Changes to restrictions on night flying have allowed for a quicker recovery of flight programmes and we welcome this more flexible approach by the Department for Transport. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What lessons have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10? What practical changes have been made to ensure the UK is now better equipped to deal with severe weather?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are pleased that Heathrow and Gatwick have invested in additional equipment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and airside operations to bolster winter resilience. We appreciate that airports need to be prudent in terms of investment and spending limited funds and acknowledge there is a balance to be struck in terms of investment in this equipment.  They have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed hard to ensure that runways, taxiways, aprons and stands are kept clear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and operational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The airlines have also invested.  British Airways</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for instance,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has purchased more de-icing rigs and has enough fully trained crews to operate its fleet of 25 rigs no matter how long the cold weather might last.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">munications have also improved between airports and the travel trade. When there is severe disruption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being able to provide correct and timely advice to passengers is essential and improvements in the way airports and the trade work together to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> achieve this are very welcome.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">irports, in consultation with their user airlines, have put in plac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e an agreed operating procedure with a reduced number of movements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the event of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disruptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although we appreciate that we have not seen weather as bad in the last two winters, a repetition of the scenes we saw at Gatwick in early December 2010 and at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Heathrow before Christmas 2010 must be avoided at all costs as it is seriously damaging to both airports’ reputations and the travel industry as a whole.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Ensuring that flights can arrive and depart in a timely manner at all times of the year is an essenti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al part of keeping Britain open for business and we encourage all those involved in this area to remain vigilant about operational improvements and focussed on delivering long-term improvements in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> managing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aviation capacity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How well prepared are the Gover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nment, local authorities and transport providers for adverse winter weather? What more should be done to ensure a coordinated response?</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ensuring airports are able to operate efficiently in the winter as well as in the summer is essential but it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">important to note that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he passenger’s journey starts at their home, not just at the airport.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With the airports striving to ensure that they are operational, it is incumbent on the local authorities and transport providers to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icy roads and rai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lways remain open to ensure that passengers, and workers, can access the airports safely.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is especially important where surface connectivity to airports is already limited or constrained, for instance at Leeds Bradford Airport where the acc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ess route i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s already limited and extreme weather can cause additional problems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It is important to note that surface access routes need to remain open not only for customers to access airports but also for staff and those employed in the airports themselves. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In conclusion, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UK is very dependent on having adequate air capacity. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ABTA strongly believes that additional capacity at our key airports is essential not only to provide for the expected growth in passengers in the coming years but to include sufficie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt resilience to allow for recovery of flight programmes in the event of disruption. Despite considerable investment at Heathrow and Gatwick airports in recent years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we remain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerned that the constrained capacity of these airports represents a considerable risk to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resilience of flights in the winter. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ABTA has long supported additional runway capacity in the South East, particularly at Heathrow and Gatwick, to a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">llow for long-term growth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and recovery of flight programmes in the event of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">severe weather or other issues affecting flights. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36.93pt; padding-left:17.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thank you for taking our comments into consideration. We would welcome the opportunity to discuss any points raised in our respo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nse further with the Committee.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>